06544nam a22009015i 9781644532942DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023deu    fo  d z      eng d  a97816445329427 a10.36019/97816445329422doi  a(DE-B1597)652462  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  adeucUS-DE 4aDC33.3b.W39 2023 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a944/.026223/eng/2022082404aThe Waxing of the Middle Ages :bRevisiting Late Medieval France /ced. by Charles-Louis Morand-Métivier, Tracy Adams. 1aNewark : bUniversity of Delaware Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (284 p.) :b19 color, 1 b-w image  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Early Modern Exchange00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Working with Huizinga’s Legacy -- tChapter one. Color Values, or Life with Grey -- tChapter two. Jean de Meun and Visual Eroticism in Fifteenth-Century Culture -- tChapter three. Jean Chartier and the End of the Historical Tradition at Saint-Denis -- tChapter four. “Present en sa personne” -- tChapter five. Rethinking Patronage in Late Medieval France -- tChapter six. The Rhétoriqueurs and the Transition from Manuscript to Print -- tChapter seven. François Villon and France -- tChapter eight. La Belle Dame of Chartier Manuscripts -- tChapter nine. Agnès Sorel, Celebrity, and Late Medieval French Visual Culture -- tChapter ten. No Job for a Man -- tConclusion: French Historians in Search of the Historiographical Identity of the French Fifteenth Century -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJohan Huizinga’s much-loved and much-contested Autumn of the Middle Ages, first published in 1919, encouraged an image of the Late French Middle Ages as a flamboyant but empty period of decline and nostalgia. Many studies, particularly literary studies, have challenged Huizinga’s perceptions of individual works or genres. Still, the vision of the Late French and Burgundian Middle Ages as a sad transitional phase between the High Middle Ages and the Renaissance persists. Yet, a series of exceptionally significant cultural developments mark the period. The Waxing of the Middle Ages sets out to provide a rich, complex, and diverse study of these developments and to reassert that late medieval France is crucial in its own right. The collection argues for an approach that views the late medieval period not as an afterthought, or a blind spot, but as a period that is key in understanding the fluidity of time, traditions, culture, and history. Each essay explores some “cultural form,” to borrow Huizinga’s expression, to expose the false divide that has dominated modern scholarship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  afrance, burgandy, history, culture, politics, middle ages, late middle ages, europe, tradition, medieval.1 aAdams, Tracy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdams, Tracy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrown, Cynthia J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Cynthia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollard, Franck, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcRae, Joan E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcRae, Joan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorand-Métivier, Charles-Louis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorand-Métivier, Charles-Louis, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNichols, Stephen G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNichols, Ste